sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1797000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Blue Light Sensing System with GFP Reporter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is a combination of BBa_K592016, BBa_K592006, and BBa_K592010 in that order. We also add a promoter called promoter 104 so that teams can use this part to test the blue light system easily. When the cells are kept in dark, they will express amilGFP, a yellow chromoprotein. This protein causes the cells to have a yellow color. When the cells are exposed to blue light, the amilGFP won't be expressed and the yellow color can't be seen.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: iGEM15_Tsinghua
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: How to add the promoter 104 into the part.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K592006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: FixK2 promoter is the wild-type promoter to which phospho-FixJ binds. FixJ in turn can be regulated by YF1, the blue light-sensing protein. This promoter shows very little leaky activity in the absence of FixJ.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lei Sun
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: FixK2 promoter omes from the genome of Bradyrhizobium japonicum.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The sequence information was provided by Moffat (Moffat et al. 2009). The DNA was synthesized by GenScript.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: FixJ
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: FixJ, the response regulator to YF1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: FixJ comes from the genome of Bradyrhizobium japonicum. It's the wild-type response regulator to YF1, the blue light-sensing fusion protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lei Sun
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: FixJ comes from the genome of Bradyrhizobium japonicum.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The sequence was information was provided by Moffat (Moffat et al. 2009). The DNA was synthesized by GenScript.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: YF1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: YF1 is a fusion protein of YtvA (B.subtilis) and FixL(Br.japonicum). It contains the N-terminal region of YtvA (1-127) and C-terminal region of FixL (258-505), interconnected by a helical linker. This fusion protein is designed by Andreas Moglich and Keith Moffat. As shown in previous research, Illumination of the fusion kinase YF1 reduced net kinase activity by ∼1000-fold in vitro. YF1 also controls gene expression in a light-dependent manner in vivo.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lei Sun
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
Ytva comes from the genome of Bacillus subtilis.
FixL derives from the genome of Bradyrhizobium japonicum.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The sequence information was provided in Moglich and Moffat's article. The physical DNA was synthesized by GenScript. Codon-optimization may enhance its expression.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: amilGFP
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This chromoprotein, amilGFP, naturally exhibits very strong yellow color when expressed. The color is strong and readily visible to naked eye both in LB-culture and on agar plates. The DNA was provided by Jeffrey Miller at UCLA. It was made BioBrick-compatible after removal of two illegal internal restriction sites (EcoRI and PstI).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lei Sun
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Two illegal internal restriction sites (EcoRI and PstI) was removed.
